    "subcategories": ["Movies", "Games", "Concerts", "Books"]
  },
  "Shopping": {
    "description": "Shopping and personal items",
    "subcategories": ["Clothing", "Electronics", "Personal Care", "Home Goods", "Gifts"]
  },
  "Bills": {
    "description": "Regular bills and subscriptions",
    "subcategories": ["Phone", "Internet", "Subscriptions", "Memberships"]
  },
  "Education": {
    "description": "Education and learning expenses",
    "subcategories": ["Tuition", "Books", "Courses", "Stationeries", "Certifications", "Workshops", "Programming-Contest", "Exam Registration"]
  },
  "Other": {
    "description": "Miscellaneous expenses",
    "subcategories": ["Donations", "Miscellaneous"]
  }
}

Analyze the input and identify all individual transactions.  
Return a JSON array of objects, each with:
  {
    "date": "YYYY-MM-DD hh:mm a (use today's date if none mentioned)",
    "category": "one of the provided main categories",
    "subcategory": "one of its subcategories",
    "amount": float,
    "description": "short description (empty if none)"
  }

Assume â€œRegular Mealâ€ for any food unless â€œDining Outâ€ or a restaurant is mentioned.  
If uncategorizable, set both category and subcategory to "Other".  
If only one transaction, return an array with one object.  
Do not invent new categories or subcategories.

